1
00:00:00,916 --> 00:00:03,625
I told you I stayed here 28 days

2
00:00:04,750 --> 00:00:08,750
Then they moved me to that house, which was also a prison

3
00:00:09,625 --> 00:00:11,000
I stayed there 10 days

4
00:00:11,916 --> 00:00:18,666
In those 10 days they put me in a course of religious instruction and <i>tawhid</i>

5
00:00:19,375 --> 00:00:21,250
When the 10 days ended they released us

6
00:00:22,666 --> 00:00:28,791
Interviewer: When they transferred you to the other prison and you stayed there 10 days

7
00:00:29,375 --> 00:00:32,791
Were you by yourself, or were you with a group?

8
00:00:32,916 --> 00:00:37,500
No, I was with a large group, more than 30 people, roughly

9
00:00:38,791 --> 00:00:40,541
Interviewer: Had those people been imprisoned for a long time?

10
00:00:42,208 --> 00:00:45,125
Some for 10 days, some stayed a month, others eight days

11
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:47,500
It depended on each person's case

12
00:00:48,125 --> 00:00:50,750
Interviewer: Can you tell me the charges they were accused of?

13
00:00:51,250 --> 00:00:52,625
One of them because of birds

14
00:00:53,250 --> 00:00:54,625
And another because of cigarettes

15
00:00:55,875 --> 00:00:58,500
And another they caught while he was smuggling cigarettes in a car

16
00:00:59,875 --> 00:01:00,916
His name was Khalil

17
00:01:03,625 --> 00:01:07,625
Various charges, most for smoking

18
00:01:08,208 --> 00:01:12,000
Interviewer: Considering there was a group of people during those 10 days

19
00:01:12,041 --> 00:01:16,916
And you had come out of solitary to a prison with a group

20
00:01:17,166 --> 00:01:21,125
How were your relationships? And how did you spend your days and nights together?

21
00:01:21,166 --> 00:01:24,041
It was normal, we talked freely

22
00:01:24,875 --> 00:01:31,375
And when the time for the lessons came

23
00:01:31,416 --> 00:01:35,625
We went out and sat in the house courtyard. We sat in pairs, and they taught us

24
00:01:36,416 --> 00:01:40,916
Interviewer: In that prison where you stayed 10 days

25
00:01:41,125 --> 00:01:44,000
Interviewer: And you were 30 people?
Witness: Yes, more than 30

26
00:01:44,041 --> 00:01:48,166
Interviewer: What were their ages, roughly the youngest to the oldest?

27
00:01:49,125 --> 00:01:52,125
There were 18-year-olds, and there were 40-year-olds

28
00:01:53,250 --> 00:01:57,208
And there were 50-year-olds—there were various ages

29
00:01:58,041 --> 00:02:00,541
Interviewer: Because of this difference between ages, between young and old

30
00:02:00,541 --> 00:02:05,208
And because of differences in mindsets and backgrounds

31
00:02:05,250 --> 00:02:10,416
Were there quarrels or problems between them, or between one group and another, while you were there?

32
00:02:10,500 --> 00:02:15,250
No, no problems happened between the prisoners at all

33
00:02:16,250 --> 00:02:21,500
On the contrary, we got along and liked each other

34
00:02:21,791 --> 00:02:23,041
Everyone helped each other

35
00:02:23,500 --> 00:02:27,250
If someone was hungry and had no food, another gave him some of his food

36
00:02:27,625 --> 00:02:28,625
We ate together, for example

37
00:02:29,250 --> 00:02:33,750
If someone had a headache we gave him a painkiller tablet

38
00:02:34,500 --> 00:02:35,625
That was how it was

39
00:02:36,250 --> 00:02:42,333
Interviewer: How did they treat you there as a group?

40
00:02:42,375 --> 00:02:44,541
When you were by yourself, you had special care

41
00:02:44,791 --> 00:02:46,916
Was the care the same there?

42
00:02:47,333 --> 00:02:48,791
Yes, there was care

43
00:02:48,916 --> 00:02:54,166
And they had a person there

44
00:02:57,666 --> 00:02:59,625
He was responsible for something like a pharmacy

45
00:03:00,875 --> 00:03:03,333
Meaning he was from ISIS

46
00:03:04,333 --> 00:03:07,041
He had a set of medicines that he gave to anyone suffering from something

47
00:03:07,041 --> 00:03:11,666
They had medications for headaches or heart conditions

48
00:03:13,375 --> 00:03:15,541
It was in the hallway, like a small pharmacy

49
00:03:16,416 --> 00:03:19,333
Interviewer: Were you allowed to move around inside there?

50
00:03:19,375 --> 00:03:21,000
It is a small house

51
00:03:21,500 --> 00:03:23,875
We wandered in its courtyard or in the room—nothing more than that

52
00:03:24,291 --> 00:03:26,333
Interviewer: Was it allowed to go out to the courtyard at any time?

53
00:03:26,375 --> 00:03:31,333
Yes, the room doors were open, and the house was fortified from the outside

54
00:03:32,625 --> 00:03:35,500
Interviewer: How many guards were there?
Witness: Five guards

55
00:03:36,625 --> 00:03:38,750
Interviewer: How did they treat you?

56
00:03:39,625 --> 00:03:41,041
It was fine, not bad

57
00:03:41,625 --> 00:03:44,375
Interviewer: Were their nationalities or accents those of Mosul locals and Bedouins?

58
00:03:44,416 --> 00:03:45,541
Or were they only from Mosul?

59
00:03:45,791 --> 00:03:50,875
They were mixed—two of them were from Diyala, as I recall

60
00:03:51,500 --> 00:03:54,625
And three were from the outskirts of Mosul

61
00:03:55,375 --> 00:03:57,916
Interviewer: Was the food there like it was here?

62
00:03:58,125 --> 00:04:00,625
Yes, they brought us the same food

63
00:04:02,125 --> 00:04:04,750
Interviewer: Was there any discrimination between one prisoner and another, or not?

64
00:04:04,750 --> 00:04:07,333
No, everyone was equal

65
00:04:08,125 --> 00:04:13,625
Interviewer: You said there was a small pharmacy

66
00:04:13,625 --> 00:04:16,041
Yes, it was small, for whoever needed a painkiller tablet

67
00:04:16,125 --> 00:04:19,416
Or, for example, someone with a sore throat, they gave him a capsule

68
00:04:21,041 --> 00:04:22,500
They dispensed the medicine for him normally

69
00:04:23,291 --> 00:04:26,916
Interviewer: This place is indeed a prison

70
00:04:27,041 --> 00:04:30,875
But as a prison, did you feel there was special care?

71
00:04:30,916 --> 00:04:34,333
Or was that, as you mentioned, because they needed

72
00:04:34,416 --> 00:04:39,041
To ask you and others to join them?

73
00:04:40,250 --> 00:04:45,625
It was varied because each person had a different case

74
00:04:47,041 --> 00:04:49,291
Interviewer: Since you were now with a group of prisoners

75
00:04:49,333 --> 00:04:51,250
How did you spend your nights and days with them?

76
00:04:51,250 --> 00:04:52,916
It was normal—it was better than here

77
00:04:53,291 --> 00:04:58,500
Interviewer: Tell me about your life and the times you spent in the prison

78
00:04:58,541 --> 00:05:02,500
We used to talk most of the time

79
00:05:03,666 --> 00:05:09,041
We got to know each other and asked where people lived, for example

80
00:05:10,666 --> 00:05:14,000
And we talked about religion in case they were listening

81
00:05:14,500 --> 00:05:16,166
They would know we were talking about religion

82
00:05:17,375 --> 00:05:19,791
We talked about religious stories and such things

83
00:05:20,333 --> 00:05:21,375
We spent time like that

84
00:05:21,750 --> 00:05:25,041
Interviewer: Do you think there were spies among you from their personnel?

85
00:05:25,041 --> 00:05:29,416
Or did they bring in people who volunteered to act as spies and pass information

86
00:05:30,250 --> 00:05:32,125
I don't know—I don't think so

87
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:37,208
I don't think any of their members were among the prisoners

88
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:46,750
Do you remember particular stories that happened during your imprisonment there over the 10 days?

89
00:05:46,791 --> 00:05:49,041
Or a specific person's story you still remember

90
00:05:49,333 --> 00:05:52,250
Or a story that affected you that you still remember

91
00:05:52,291 --> 00:05:55,625
And it hurts when you remember it

92
00:05:55,916 --> 00:05:58,666
Or a case of a particular person that happened in front of you?

93
00:05:58,916 --> 00:06:00,916
Or a particular injustice?

94
00:06:01,333 --> 00:06:03,041
It was all injustice

95
00:06:04,875 --> 00:06:06,291
Because we were all unjustly imprisoned

96
00:06:07,500 --> 00:06:08,750
Can someone be imprisoned because of cigarettes?

97
00:06:09,375 --> 00:06:12,041
It was all injustice, like the one they brought because of cigarettes

98
00:06:12,125 --> 00:06:17,500
And the one they brought and flogged because he’d said a word outside to his friend

99
00:06:17,500 --> 00:06:19,041
Trivial things

100
00:06:20,125 --> 00:06:25,416
Interviewer: Weren't there any charges more serious than cigarettes?

101
00:06:25,791 --> 00:06:28,750
Or did they bring someone unjustly when he didn’t even have cigarettes?

102
00:06:29,875 --> 00:06:34,375
Most of them were family matters

103
00:06:35,041 --> 00:06:39,916
Meaning they would also bring someone who had a problem with his wife, or whose voice was loud

104
00:06:41,541 --> 00:06:43,333
Interviewer: They hear his voice and then bring him?

105
00:06:43,375 --> 00:06:45,333
Someone files a complaint against him

106
00:06:46,791 --> 00:06:49,500
Meaning they had operatives everywhere

107
00:06:50,416 --> 00:06:52,666
For example, they hear that someone blasphemed, so they bring him

108
00:06:53,375 --> 00:06:57,333
Or if someone blasphemes, they would behead him on the spot

109
00:06:59,291 --> 00:07:01,791
Interviewer: How did you spend your time in the prison?

110
00:07:02,625 --> 00:07:10,041
They gave us papers containing religious material to memorize

111
00:07:10,750 --> 00:07:15,541
Quranic verses and suras, and <i>tawhid</i> material to memorize

112
00:07:16,500 --> 00:07:19,500
And instruction, and such things

113
00:07:20,500 --> 00:07:22,000
Interviewer: Did you memorize them as lessons?

114
00:07:22,375 --> 00:07:23,875
Yes, they asked us in the morning when we woke up

115
00:07:25,916 --> 00:07:28,333
Interviewer: So lessons and homework?
Witness: Yes

116
00:07:28,875 --> 00:07:31,541
They gave us three or four pages of paper

117
00:07:32,541 --> 00:07:34,416
We memorized them and in the morning we answered their questions

118
00:07:34,416 --> 00:07:36,208
No one is unaware of these things

119
00:07:36,250 --> 00:07:39,750
Everyone knows the Ibrahimiyya prayers

120
00:07:39,750 --> 00:07:42,875
We all had them memorized

121
00:07:44,041 --> 00:07:46,625
Interviewer: So it was like a school
Witness: Yes, almost

122
00:07:47,291 --> 00:07:49,916
Interviewer: What kind of lessons were they?

123
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:51,625
And who was the person who taught you?

124
00:07:51,666 --> 00:07:53,541
Was it the same person who came every time?

125
00:07:53,625 --> 00:07:55,791
Yes, it was the same person and his name was Abu Muhammad

126
00:07:57,166 --> 00:07:59,791
Interviewer: Was it the same one who came daily? Didn't someone else come?

127
00:07:59,875 --> 00:08:00,916
No, the same one came

128
00:08:01,416 --> 00:08:03,666
Interviewer: Can you describe to me what he looked like?

129
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:07,625
Was he actually a teacher by profession, or did he teach in a mosque?

130
00:08:07,625 --> 00:08:09,250
Yes, he was a teacher

131
00:08:10,500 --> 00:08:13,250
He was a teacher and about 40 years old

132
00:08:14,625 --> 00:08:16,250
He had great knowledge of religion

133
00:08:17,500 --> 00:08:19,500
He asked us and encouraged us

134
00:08:20,416 --> 00:08:23,750
To memorize and read the Quran

135
00:08:26,250 --> 00:08:27,750
Interviewer: What was the type of lessons exactly?

136
00:08:27,791 --> 00:08:33,291
Were the lessons related to jurisprudence and matters of purification, prayer, and creed?

137
00:08:33,291 --> 00:08:37,125
Or were there lessons you think they intended to push you to pledge allegiance?

138
00:08:37,166 --> 00:08:39,041
Were they advising you to pledge allegiance?

139
00:08:39,208 --> 00:08:43,750
And did they try to show you they were in the right, and so on?

140
00:08:43,750 --> 00:08:44,875
Was that the case?

141
00:08:44,875 --> 00:08:47,625
Yes, that's right—those things were there

142
00:08:48,208 --> 00:08:49,750
Interviewer: How so? What did they ask you, for example?

143
00:08:49,791 --> 00:08:51,250
And how did they deal with you on this matter?

144
00:08:52,791 --> 00:08:55,791
Honestly I don't know what to say to you

145
00:08:57,500 --> 00:08:59,250
Meaning they wanted us to join them

146
00:09:00,750 --> 00:09:02,875
Interviewer: Through the lessons?
Witness: Yes, through the lessons

147
00:09:03,750 --> 00:09:07,291
Interviewer: Through the lessons, did you receive an explicit call to pledge allegiance?

148
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:10,500
Yes, they openly asked if anyone wanted to pledge allegiance

149
00:09:10,541 --> 00:09:12,041
Interviewer: Did a pledge of allegiance happen in the prison?

150
00:09:12,041 --> 00:09:16,000
No, during my 10 days there, that did not happen

151
00:09:17,333 --> 00:09:22,041
But young boys would come to Sheikh Shaban Mosque

152
00:09:22,291 --> 00:09:24,125
Which is Abu Dharr al-Ghifari Mosque

153
00:09:24,750 --> 00:09:30,500
They brought young children who didn't know anything

154
00:09:31,625 --> 00:09:35,416
They tricked them into pledging allegiance

155
00:09:37,041 --> 00:09:39,041
And brought them in to make them part of their members

156
00:09:39,500 --> 00:09:41,375
Interviewer: You mentioned the mosque is Sheikh Shaban Mosque

157
00:09:41,416 --> 00:09:42,750
Is its name Sheikh Shaban Mosque?

158
00:09:42,791 --> 00:09:45,500
No, its name is Abu Dharr al-Ghifari Mosque

159
00:09:46,250 --> 00:09:51,916
But at that time there was a man named Sheikh Shaban in this mosque

160
00:09:52,208 --> 00:09:56,875
Interviewer: Do you mean they pledged allegiance with him?

161
00:09:56,875 --> 00:09:58,625
No, he was the one in charge of the mosque

162
00:09:59,375 --> 00:10:01,666
Interviewer: Who is this Sheikh Shaban?
Witness: He is from the local area

163
00:10:02,166 --> 00:10:03,208
Interviewer: Is he still around now?

164
00:10:03,500 --> 00:10:06,166
No, he isn't—he's in the north or in Turkey, I think

165
00:10:06,208 --> 00:10:08,291
Interviewer: Why is he in the north?
Witness: He hasn't come back

166
00:10:09,500 --> 00:10:11,750
He is one of their supporters

167
00:10:13,125 --> 00:10:15,125
Interviewer: Was he a supporter of ISIS?

168
00:10:15,333 --> 00:10:16,625
Yes, more or less a supporter

169
00:10:16,666 --> 00:10:20,500
Interviewer: Do you mean he went out there to escape?
Witness: Yes, he escaped

170
00:10:21,041 --> 00:10:22,750
Interviewer: His house and the money he had here, where did they go?

171
00:10:22,791 --> 00:10:24,500
I think they were confiscated

172
00:10:25,916 --> 00:10:29,375
Interviewer: Given that this man is from your area

173
00:10:29,541 --> 00:10:32,625
Did you know he supported ISIS, or did you find out after they came in?

174
00:10:32,666 --> 00:10:35,541
No, after they came in, he joined them out of fear

175
00:10:36,875 --> 00:10:38,625
Interviewer: And he is a religious man?
Witness: Yes, a religious man

176
00:10:40,125 --> 00:10:42,625
Interviewer: Did he really join them out of fear?

177
00:10:43,291 --> 00:10:44,916
ISIS are criminals

178
00:10:47,041 --> 00:10:48,250
Out of fear, anything can happen

179
00:10:48,750 --> 00:10:51,500
Interviewer: You were more afraid than him in prison, and you are not a religious man

180
00:10:51,541 --> 00:10:52,541
Why didn’t you join them?

181
00:10:52,625 --> 00:10:56,500
I would not join them, because I knew the government would return

182
00:10:57,041 --> 00:10:58,791
And that they would fall and the movie would end

183
00:11:01,208 --> 00:11:02,250
This group is manufactured

184
00:11:04,375 --> 00:11:08,375
Interviewer: Since you were with the group for 10 days

185
00:11:09,125 --> 00:11:11,750
And you said the food was the same and of the same kind

186
00:11:12,500 --> 00:11:16,750
Regarding your use of the bathrooms, since you were a large group

187
00:11:16,875 --> 00:11:18,916
How many toilets and showers were there?

188
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:20,041
There was only one

189
00:11:20,125 --> 00:11:22,208
Interviewer: And you were more than 30 people?
Witness: Yes

190
00:11:22,250 --> 00:11:25,500
Interviewer: Was there any kind of schedule for going to the bathroom?

191
00:11:25,500 --> 00:11:27,625
Yes, it had to be quick in the morning

192
00:11:27,750 --> 00:11:31,166
Anyone who wanted to use the toilet had to hurry

193
00:11:31,250 --> 00:11:33,125
So the one behind him could go in

194
00:11:33,750 --> 00:11:35,541
Then the third, the fourth, and so on

195
00:11:35,666 --> 00:11:37,666
Interviewer: So it was up to you

196
00:11:37,750 --> 00:11:43,125
Yes, it was just a house, guarded by ISIS members

197
00:11:43,291 --> 00:11:46,208
But we were at ease, going to the toilet and so on

198
00:11:46,416 --> 00:11:49,041
Interviewer: Were cleaning supplies and soap available?

199
00:11:49,125 --> 00:11:50,416
Yes, they were available

200
00:11:50,750 --> 00:11:53,000
Interviewer: You were more than 30 people, so your number was large

201
00:11:53,041 --> 00:11:54,916
Did you have a cleaning schedule?

202
00:11:54,916 --> 00:11:56,666
Were two or three people cleaning daily?

203
00:11:56,750 --> 00:12:00,500
Yes, every day four people would clean a room

204
00:12:00,791 --> 00:12:02,125
There were two rooms

205
00:12:03,250 --> 00:12:05,416
Interviewer: Were the four from the prisoners or from ISIS members?

206
00:12:05,500 --> 00:12:06,500
They were prisoners

207
00:12:06,500 --> 00:12:09,666
Interviewer: Did they set a schedule for you, or was it among you?

208
00:12:09,750 --> 00:12:13,000
Among ourselves, for example me and my friends

209
00:12:13,166 --> 00:12:15,791
We would be four, for example, and say we will do the cleaning today

210
00:12:16,791 --> 00:12:19,625
The next day, another four would do the cleaning

211
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:24,875
They cleaned the sleeping area, swept, and wiped it with Dettol and a towel

212
00:12:26,250 --> 00:12:28,500
Interviewer: Were disinfectants also available?
Witness: Yes

213
00:12:28,666 --> 00:12:33,000
Interviewer: Did any prisoner develop a skin disease?

214
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:36,625
No, that did not happen, because the period was short

215
00:12:37,625 --> 00:12:40,625
Interviewer: Did any prisoner suffer from a chronic illness?

216
00:12:40,750 --> 00:12:42,750
And did he have a special kind of food?

217
00:12:44,208 --> 00:12:47,250
A person who had a chronic illness, a heart condition, or other issues

218
00:12:47,500 --> 00:12:48,750
Had his medication with him

219
00:12:50,166 --> 00:12:53,791
Interviewer: And if his medicine ran out, would they bring him some?
Witness: Yes, they would give it to him

220
00:12:55,291 --> 00:12:57,416
Interviewer: Did it happen that someone asked them for treatment

221
00:12:57,500 --> 00:12:59,125
Interviewer: And did they tell him they didn’t have it?
Witness: No

222
00:12:59,625 --> 00:13:02,250
Interviewer: So if it was not available in the pharmacy, would they bring it from outside?

223
00:13:02,250 --> 00:13:05,250
Yes, they would bring it from outside

224
00:13:05,500 --> 00:13:08,750
Interviewer: You mentioned that the jailers’ treatment of you was normal

225
00:13:09,541 --> 00:13:13,208
Interviewer: Didn’t a judge come to you there?
Witness: They came for visits

226
00:13:13,625 --> 00:13:15,916
Interviewer: Did they come for interrogation?
Witness: No, they came for visits

227
00:13:16,500 --> 00:13:17,916
They would look over the place

228
00:13:18,916 --> 00:13:20,791
They called him <i>al-Hajji</i>, and we did not know who he was

229
00:13:20,916 --> 00:13:25,041
During that visit, was there direct contact and conversation with you as prisoners?

230
00:13:25,041 --> 00:13:27,875
Yes, they would ask us how the brothers treated us

231
00:13:28,208 --> 00:13:31,250
Meaning ISIS members, and we would tell him their treatment was good

232
00:13:33,666 --> 00:13:36,041
That was all, and we could not say more than that

233
00:13:37,125 --> 00:13:39,875
And even if their treatment was not good, we would say it was good

234
00:13:41,583 --> 00:13:43,916
Interviewer: Did torture or flogging happen there?
Witness: No, there was no torture

235
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:45,291
Interviewer: Was there no flogging?
Witness: No

236
00:13:46,250 --> 00:13:48,500
Interviewer: And no one was punished there?
Witness: No

237
00:13:48,500 --> 00:13:50,125
Interviewer: Absolutely?
Witness: Yes, absolutely

238
00:13:50,166 --> 00:13:53,291
I told you we were comfortable

239
00:13:53,750 --> 00:13:54,916
Interviewer: How did they get you out of the prison?

240
00:13:55,416 --> 00:13:57,250
The course ended, so I left

241
